<Layout title="Giving Your Tenant Notice to Vacate When Selling Your Brisbane Property | Daniel Gierach Property" description="A practical guide for landlords selling a tenanted Brisbane investment property, covering notice periods, your tenant's rights, and how to manage the process without derailing settlement." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much notice do I need to give my tenant to vacate when selling my Brisbane property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "For a periodic tenancy (month-to-month), you need to give two months written notice to leave, with the reason and the vacate date specified. For a fixed-term tenancy, you cannot terminate during the fixed term simply because you want to sell. The lease must run its course, or the buyer must agree to take on the tenancy at settlement."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I force my tenant to leave because I want to sell my investment property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. Under the Residential Tenancies and Rooming Accommodation Act 2008 (Qld), a landlord cannot evict a tenant solely because they want to sell. For a periodic tenancy, you can issue a Notice to Leave with two months notice. For a fixed-term tenancy, the lease must be honoured or the buyer agrees to take it on."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What happens if my tenant refuses to leave after I give notice?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If a tenant refuses to vacate after receiving a valid Notice to Leave, the matter is referred to the Queensland Civil and Administrative Tribunal (QCAT). This process can cause significant delays to your settlement timeline. Early communication, a good landlord-tenant relationship, and in some cases offering a relocation payment are the most effective ways to avoid this outcome."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
