        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        &larr; All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 6 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Giving Your Tenant Notice to Vacate When Selling Your Brisbane Investment Property
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Selling a tenanted property in Queensland is manageable, but only if you understand what the law allows, when to act, and how to keep the process from derailing your settlement.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>If you own an investment property in Brisbane and you have decided to sell, one of the first questions you need to answer is what happens to your tenant. The answer is not simply to tell them to leave. Queensland tenancy law gives tenants real protections, and ignoring those protections can delay or derail your settlement. Understanding the process early is what separates a smooth sale from a stressful one.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The fundamental rule you need to understand</h2>
      <p>Under the Residential Tenancies and Rooming Accommodation Act 2008 (Qld), a landlord cannot terminate a tenancy simply because they want to sell. The desire to sell is not, on its own, a valid ground for eviction. The type of tenancy your tenant is on determines what you can and cannot do, and when you can do it.</p>

      <p>Most landlords selling investment properties in Brisbane are surprised to discover that the law is quite specific here. Getting this wrong creates disputes, QCAT hearings, and in the worst cases, failed settlements where buyers are unable to get vacant possession on the agreed date.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Periodic tenancy: what you can do</h2>
      <p>A periodic tenancy, also called a month-to-month tenancy, is the most common arrangement once a fixed-term lease has expired without being renewed. If your tenant is on a periodic tenancy, you can issue a Notice to Leave specifying that the reason for the notice is that the property has been sold (or that the owner requires vacant possession to facilitate a sale). The required notice period is two months.</p>

      <p>The notice must be in writing, must state the reason, and must specify the vacate date. Your property manager handles the formal notice. If you try to issue the notice yourself without going through the correct process, it can be challenged and declared invalid, resetting the clock.</p>

      <p>The timing of when you issue the notice matters significantly. If you want vacant possession at settlement and your settlement date is, for example, two months away, the notice needs to be issued immediately. Most experienced sellers issue the notice as soon as they decide to sell, even before the property is officially listed. This gives the tenant the required notice period and aligns the vacate date with or before your target settlement date.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Fixed-term tenancy: what you cannot do</h2>
      <p>If your tenant is in the middle of a fixed-term lease, you cannot terminate that lease simply because you want to sell. The lease is a binding contract that runs to its end date. You have two realistic options: wait for the lease to expire before listing, or sell with the tenant in place and market the property as an investment to buyers who are comfortable taking on the existing tenancy at settlement.</p>

      <p>Selling with a tenant in place is a different kind of campaign. Your buyer pool narrows to investors rather than owner-occupiers. Open homes require appropriate notice to the tenant (at least 24 hours in writing, and the tenant's cooperation, which is not guaranteed). The buyer steps into your shoes as landlord at settlement, inheriting the lease terms, the bond, and the ongoing relationship with the tenant.</p>

      <p>If you are selling a property with a long-term fixed tenancy in place, be transparent about the situation in your marketing from the start. Investors who are comfortable with the tenancy terms and the rental return will engage with the property on its merits. Attempting to obscure the tenancy situation wastes everyone's time and sometimes creates legal exposure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to give your agent before the campaign starts</h2>
      <p>Before you list, provide your selling agent with a copy of the current lease agreement, confirmation of whether a Notice to Leave has been issued (and the date and vacate date if so), the current rent amount and when it was last reviewed, and the bond amount and where it is lodged. Buyers and their solicitors will ask for this information. Having it ready avoids delays and shows that you have managed the property properly.</p>

      <p>Your property manager and your selling agent need to communicate with each other. Breakdowns between the two are a common cause of last-minute problems. If your property manager is handling the tenant notice process, make sure your selling agent knows the timeline and that both parties are working to the same settlement target.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens if the tenant refuses to vacate</h2>
      <p>If a tenant receives a valid Notice to Leave and refuses to vacate by the specified date, the matter must be referred to QCAT (Queensland Civil and Administrative Tribunal). QCAT can issue a termination order, but the process takes time, typically weeks, not days. This can directly threaten your settlement timeline and create significant stress for both you and your buyer.</p>

      <p>The best protection against this scenario is a good landlord-tenant relationship built over the life of the tenancy. Tenants who have been well managed, had their maintenance requests attended to promptly, and been treated respectfully are far more likely to cooperate with a notice to leave than those who feel they have been poorly treated. This is worth keeping in mind throughout the investment period, not just when you decide to sell.</p>

      <p>Some landlords choose to offer a voluntary payment to the tenant to vacate by the required date. This is not required by law, but it can be a practical way to secure cooperation and avoid the QCAT process. Whether this makes sense depends on the rental amount, your timeline, and the specific circumstances of your tenant. Your property manager can advise on this.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Start the process early</h2>
      <p>The single most common mistake landlords make when selling a tenanted property is leaving the notice too late. Two months is not a long time when you are also preparing the property, engaging an agent, and running a campaign. If you are planning to sell in the next six months, speak to your property manager now about your options. The earlier you start the process, the more control you have over the timeline and the lower the risk of a disrupted settlement.</p>

